  .article-section.article-section-right-image.text-first.article-half-page-image-floated
    .article-text
      %h3
        SIZE AND COMFORT - HOW TO GET THE FIT RIGHT

      .article-image.aspect-2-3
        -image_url = image_path("blog/winter-jumpers/big-cream-jumper-snow.jpg")
        =image_tag(image_url, alt: "A lady sits on a blanket on the snow-covered steps outside her house. She wears a warm oversized cream jumper with a high neck, long socks to match and warm suede house shoes.")
        %figcaption
          Photo by
          =link_to('prostooleh', 'https://www.freepik.com/free-photo/close-up-portrait-lady-white-sweater-sitting-by-home-terrace_13181721.htm')
          on Freepik

      %p
        Jumpers are no longer in the one size fits all category.
        They have not been for quite some time, so there is no excuse for still trying to get some wear out of that ill-fitting, overstretched one you still have in your wardrobe.
        Unless it is for Sunday couch day, right?
        Jumpers now come in all shapes and flattering sizes and there are many levels of comfort too.
        So it’s important to build your knowledge to save you buying the wrong type of wool for you.
        If anything, quality has not been reduced in the process, and affordability has improved greatly across the board.

      %p
        So let’s ask a good question.
        How do you view your current favourite jumper?
        It's important to know how you see your current top jumper.
        Do you use your current favourite jumpers as more of a reason to cover up and hide in winter?
        Do you think of it as more of an opportunity to be comfortable than stylish?
        A good jumper in the right size will give you heaps of confidence and comfort all in one.
        The key is to know what style to go for and how to wear it.
        Do you think you are wearing the right size jumper for you?
        Are your jumpers the right size to complement your size and frame best?
        I have created a mini guide so you can check how you are doing.

      %p
        So, here are my quick tips on jumpers and shaping:

      %h4
        Wearing the right size jumper for your shape - a quick guide

      %p
        %ul
          %li
            Small frames - go for more fitted and shorter knits.
            These will even out your proportions and elongate legs from the waist down.
            Wear them with jeans or shorter length skirts.
          %li
            Medium frames – mid lengths can really work for medium frames and comfortably cover a mid-size waist, if you prefer to.
            Wear knee length boots and leggings or mid length skirts for a good balance to your overall frame.
          %li
            Larger frames – longer lengths will elongate the upper frame proportionally and give more overall balance.
            One option is to wear them as dresses with tights.

  .article-section.article-section-right-image.text-first.article-half-page-image-floated
    .article-text
      %h3
        COLOUR AND SHAPE - KNOWING WHAT SUITS YOU AND WHY 

      .article-image.aspect-2-3
        -image_url = image_path("blog/winter-jumpers/city-knitwear.jpg")
        =image_tag(image_url, alt: "A lady wears a loose cream jumper with texture coming from the contoured lines of the knit. It is a sunny autumn day so she wears sunglasses and carries her long trenchcoat.")
        %figcaption
          Photo by
          =link_to('standret', 'https://www.freepik.com/free-photo/holds-coat-hand-young-beautiful-girl-warm-clothes-have-walk-city-her-weekends-time_9819579.htm')
          on Freepik

      %p
        When it comes to colour we all have a favourite that we go for.
        I call it the 'safe colour’, and every wardrobe has one.
        Do you know what your safe colour is?
        Maybe you have never thought about it, or are not really sure.
        Most people choose darker colours.
        Try this test out on your wardrobe, to find out what your safe colour is.  

      %p
        Take a look in your wardrobe and tell me what you see.
        You are looking for the most evident colour you can see in your wardrobe.
        The colour that stands out the most is probably your safe colour.
        Black is the most popular safe colour, for obvious reasons.
        It goes with everything and it's flattering and kind to any shape or size.
        But, in the midst of winter, you might feel like you want something a little uplifting, something a little brighter in colour, or with a touch more elegance and style.
        Something to give you that soft warm hug that only a good winter jumper can give.
        Maybe you have always thought that winter colours need to be darker or a bit solemn, but there are quite a few brighter winter colours to choose from.
        Try this simple exercise.

      %p
        What colours come to mind, when you think of warmth?
        Is it a nice yellow sun or a cozy warm burgundy?
        Maybe it’s a nice red hot fire or a soft dark grey blanket?
        How many different colours did you think of?

      %p
        How we see colour is important to how it makes us feel.
        There is burgundy, grey, black, purple, red, pink, cream, blue, green, white and all the different shades in between and they all connect to a certain emotion for us personally.
        So think about your connection to colour in winter.
        How do you view colours for winter jumpers colours now?
        Will you think about finding a lovely new colour to try now?

      %p
        If you try a new colour, the key is to still make sure that it does still match up with the rest of your wardrobe.
        There is no point in buying a new colour that does not complement anything you plan on wearing over the winter months.
        It will just sit at the back of your wardrobe because you don’t know what to wear it with.
        So, use your current wardrobe as a base and foundation to start with what you know, and build from there.

      %h4
        What shape is going to be right for you?

      %p
        Jumpers are not exactly considered fine tailoring are they?
        But there is a craft involved so you may as well go for some level of quality.
        It may appear that shape and size are often an afterthought when it comes to jumpers.
        You might also think that most people go for something big and baggy and leave it at that.
        But, let me ask you a quick question.
        How often have you seen a well-shaped jumper on someone you passed by and you wondered which brand it was from?

      %p
        Some wools are so fine and soft that they deserve nothing less than a perfect fit.
        Some wools are so chunky that it doesn’t matter what shape they are.
        So how do you decide if fine and fitted is for you?
        The best way to look at this is to think about the type of occasions you often wear a nice top for.
        A fine jumper is no different.

      %p
        You might not want to go out all night until the early hours in a fine knit, but
        Any special occasion like a nice family dinner is a perfect setting for wearing one.
        Have you ever considered that before?
        It is also a perfectly uplifting treat in the wintertime and therefore very deserving of a lovely soft knit too.

      %p
        Thinking about occasions and purpose a little more will guide you to when and where you might wear a nice fine jumper and you can start to invest in finding one as soon as possible.

  .article-section.article-section-right-image.text-first.article-half-page-image-floated
    .article-text

      %h3
        CUFFS, NECKLINE AND OTHER EMBELLISHMENTS

      .article-image.aspect-4-5
        -image_url = image_path("blog/winter-jumpers/grey-knit-sleeves.jpg")
        =image_tag(image_url, alt: "A lady wears a chunky pale grey woolen jumper with an open-knit jersey texture in the body and richly textured sleeves looking like interlocking tubes of yarn.")
        %figcaption
          Photo by
          =link_to('ansiia', 'https://www.freepik.com/free-photo/inside-portrait-adorable-lovely-lady-with-blond-hair-wearing-knitted-pullover-is-posing-isolated-background-with-romantic-smile-beautiful-lady-is-posing-during-photoshoot_26503032.htm')
          on Freepik


      %p
        It's time to talk about embellishment now.
        Have you ever taken the time to think about the subject before?
        Embellishment has been the root of many wasted purchases for quite some time.
        Why is this?
        Depending on the specific locations and amount of embellishment that a jumper has, could determine the level of comfort you have in wearing it.
        Does this make sense?

      %p
        A high level of embellishment may look amazing on first sight, but in reality if it is in inconvenient places, then it may not be that comfortable to wear it so often, therefore limiting the amount of use it gets and the value you get from owning the item.
        So, my advice would be to buy with caution if you're not used to wearing a heavily embellished jumper and don’t be enamoured by over-embellishment or something that looks like nothing you have ever seen before.

      %p
        If you do want a highly embellished knit to wear, then make sure that it is comfortable enough so you can wear it for a number of hours and you can keep it looking as lovely as it did when you first saw it in the store.
        A safe choice would be to start with a good simple and well-made jumper that has little or no embellishment at all.
        But in case you do see something that you instantly fall in love with, then thoroughly check on the type of embellishment or detail and how intricate it appears to be.
        You could also look for embellishment that is a little more subtle.
        Like an embellished cuff area or a nice styled neckline.
        Less is definitely more here.
        It’s more manageable for sure.
        So choose wisely ladies.

      %p
        Details on jumpers are not to be sniffed at.
        The skill required to coiffure any type of wool into a stylish cuff, or sleeve is something to be appreciated.
        I have seen sleeves that were such a work of art that you would never imagine they were made out of a simple ball of wool.
        So, how do you know what is considered a good amount of detail and what is not?

      %p
        It's always hard not to be impressed by fine elaborate details, but I would always advise to err on the side of caution here.
        Why?
        Because what might look delightful in the store might not fit quite so well in your life.
        What does this mean exactly?
        Well, let me explain.
        The level of detail comes partly down to three things: your day to day taste, your expected frequency of wear, and your ability to care.
        Highly embellished jumpers may look pretty in the store, but may not be quite as  that practical as you think for everyday wear.
        Lets go through the three points in more detail.

      %h4
        1.Your day to day taste

      %p
        It is better to be realistic about your everyday wear.
        Do you think you will wear a highly embellished or delicate jumper every week.
        Is this going to be practical for you and comfortable in your daily tasks?
        Are you going to be able to keep good acre of it whilst you wear it?

      %h4
        2.Your expected frequency of wear

      %p
        This is where you have to be really honest about what you expect.
        High expectations can lead to a bad purchase and even wasted money.
        If you expect to wear a jumper weekly, then it might be better to go for something that will last in frequently wearing schedule.
        Delicate embellishments don’t usually keep so well in heavy wear situations.
        So be careful and make sure that your expected wear schedule matches with the delicacy of your jumper.

      %h4
        3.Your ability to care
      
      %p
        This is your ability and willingness to care for your jumper.
        Most delicate or highly embellished jumpers need special care.
        They made need hand washing and delicate air drying or even a dry cleaning.
        So, be realistic about what you are prepared to do to care for your delicate jumper.
        Are you really likely to hand wash it or take it to the dry cleaners and go get it again every week?
        Do you have the time or budget for either of these options?
        To understand more on care take a look at my cost of care section further below. 

      %p
        So to recap, do be realistic and think about your expected frequency of use and wear and also the level of care that you can offer to your jumper during use. 

