      %h3
        COST OF CARE – KNOW YOUR CARE CAPABILITIES AND LIMITS

      .article-image.aspect-2-3
        -image_url = image_path("blog/winter-jumpers/brown-wool-jumper.jpg")
        =image_tag(image_url, alt: "A lady stands on a pebble beach wearing a pale brown waffled woolen jumper.")
        %figcaption
          Photo by
          =link_to('Holiak', 'https://www.freepik.com/free-photo/pretty-young-lady-cozy-wear-near-sea_27685821.htm')
          on Freepik

      %p
        Caring for wool can be a little bit different.
        It’s quite a delicate and a natural fibre at the end of the day, so it sometimes needs a little more care and consideration than a standard 60-degree wash followed by a fast spin cycle.
        Do you have a jumper that is a bit bothersome when it comes to washing it?
        Do you find it usually spends anything up to six months at the bottom of the washing basket waiting to be washed and only a month in the wardrobe waiting to be worn?

      %h4
        Money guilt

      %p
        The true cost of care is not just about your time, it's about your money too.
        If you already find yourself putting in more time to keep a jumper clean than time spent wearing it, then this is not the right jumper for you and your lifestyle.

      %p
        But what about the cost?
        Have you considered that side as well?
        Do you have a jumper that already fits this description?
        I would like to ask you a few questions about it.
        Did you overspend on this jumper?
        Did you fall in love with it as soon as you saw it?
        Was it more than you usually pay for a winter jumper?
        Then you may have found yourself stuck in what I call a ‘money guilt cycle’.

      %p
        Do you still have this jumper?
        Do you wash it, only when you can be bothered?
        Do you wear it less and less now?
        Has the reality and cost of care lessened the enjoyment of wearing this item?
        Because you may have spent more money on it than you normally would have done, you have to keep it because of the money guilt.
        Are you reminded of that money every time you see your jumper sat at the bottom of the washing basket?
        This is the money guilt reminder setting in.

      %p
        My advice would be to sell it, learn from the lesson and buy better next time, and don’t be fooled by fabulous-looking knitwear that costs the earth but has no realistic way of cleaning and caring for it.

      %p
        Buying better should always include being able to easily care for an item.
        Always check the washing instructions before you part with any cash.
        This is my golden rule.

